00:40:31.014 --> 00:40:32.990
CATHERINE DRENNAN:
So that's an example

00:40:32.990 --> 00:40:36.350
of how you have a
shift between two

00:40:36.350 --> 00:40:39.130
states, an inactive
and active state,

00:40:39.130 --> 00:40:41.810
that it's just a
chemical equilibrium.

00:40:41.810 --> 00:40:44.480
And binding one thing shifts
the equilibrium one way.

00:40:44.480 --> 00:40:46.190
Binding something
else shifts it back.

00:40:46.190 --> 00:40:47.990
So chemical equilibrium--
a lot of nature

00:40:47.990 --> 00:40:51.500
works by just suddenly
shifting the equilibrium

00:40:51.500 --> 00:40:53.060
between different states.

00:40:53.060 --> 00:40:54.770
So understanding
chemical equilibrium

00:40:54.770 --> 00:40:56.191
is pretty important.

00:40:56.191 --> 00:40:56.690
All right.

00:40:56.690 --> 00:41:02.300
So now we're going to apply
stress to our chemical

00:41:02.300 --> 00:41:07.180
equilibrium, and we're going to
talk about the principle of Le

00:41:07.180 --> 00:41:09.630
Chatelier.

00:41:09.630 --> 00:41:15.650
So here, a system in equilibrium
that's subject to stress

00:41:15.650 --> 00:41:23.750
will react in a way that
tends to minimize that stress.

00:41:23.750 --> 00:41:26.240
And whenever I talk to
MIT students about this,

00:41:26.240 --> 00:41:30.410
I feel like I need to
really emphasize this point.

00:41:30.410 --> 00:41:34.040
MIT students experience
a lot of stress,

00:41:34.040 --> 00:41:37.040
but often do not tend
to react in a way

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:39.920
to minimize that stress.

00:41:39.920 --> 00:41:43.850
They say, all right, I am just
struggling with this double

00:41:43.850 --> 00:41:44.360
major.

00:41:44.360 --> 00:41:45.660
I don't know what to do.

00:41:45.660 --> 00:41:46.890
It's just so much work.

00:41:46.890 --> 00:41:50.003
So maybe I should
triple major instead.

00:41:50.003 --> 00:41:50.502
No.

00:41:50.502 --> 00:41:53.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:53.160 --> 00:41:55.830
Ask yourself, what
would Le Chatelier do?

00:41:55.830 --> 00:41:56.600
Minimize.

00:41:56.600 --> 00:42:00.860
Double major, single major.

00:42:00.860 --> 00:42:04.010
So this is a principle that
can apply to your life.

00:42:04.010 --> 00:42:08.942
And I recently saw a chemistry
major, and we had lunch.

00:42:08.942 --> 00:42:10.650
He was a former MIT
student, and now he's

00:42:10.650 --> 00:42:13.580
a CEO of a company, small
company, in Cambridge

00:42:13.580 --> 00:42:18.050
that's designing computer
software platforms.

00:42:18.050 --> 00:42:21.260
He was a chemistry major, and
he's doing software design

00:42:21.260 --> 00:42:24.620
and building like
little computer tablet

00:42:24.620 --> 00:42:26.010
things for restaurants.

00:42:26.010 --> 00:42:28.780
So I said, would you use
your chemistry at all?

00:42:28.780 --> 00:42:31.490
And he goes, oh, I use some
things all the time, especially

00:42:31.490 --> 00:42:33.080
Le Chatelier's principle.

00:42:33.080 --> 00:42:35.510
I'm all about
minimizing the stress.

00:42:35.510 --> 00:42:38.090
So that was one
thing that he really

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:40.430
grabbed onto in chemistry.

00:42:40.430 --> 00:42:43.220
So again, if you
think about this,

00:42:43.220 --> 00:42:47.240
about minimizing the
stress, you can predict

00:42:47.240 --> 00:42:48.515
the direction of the reaction.

00:42:48.515 --> 00:42:51.140
And in nature, this
really works pretty well.

00:42:51.140 --> 00:42:53.090
So Le Chatelier's
principle gives us

00:42:53.090 --> 00:42:56.210
a way to predict the
direction the reaction will

00:42:56.210 --> 00:43:03.530
go if you ask, which direction
will minimize the stress?

00:43:03.530 --> 00:43:05.760
So let's look at an example.

00:43:05.760 --> 00:43:09.680
We're back to N2 and
H2 making ammonia.

00:43:09.680 --> 00:43:12.890
So here's a slightly different
plot than I drew over here.

00:43:12.890 --> 00:43:15.350
Now, this is a reaction
sensitive to temperature,

00:43:15.350 --> 00:43:16.850
so the equilibrium
constant's going

00:43:16.850 --> 00:43:18.030
to change with temperature.

00:43:18.030 --> 00:43:20.488
So every plot of this may look
a little different depending

00:43:20.488 --> 00:43:22.580
on what temperature it's at.

00:43:22.580 --> 00:43:24.364
But some things are the same.

00:43:24.364 --> 00:43:26.030
If you start with
hydrogen and nitrogen,

00:43:26.030 --> 00:43:27.980
you'll have some of
those to begin with.

00:43:27.980 --> 00:43:29.750
They will be above 0.

00:43:29.750 --> 00:43:32.630
But ammonia will start--
if you had no product,

00:43:32.630 --> 00:43:34.984
you'll have ammonia at
0 and it'll rise in.

00:43:34.984 --> 00:43:36.650
The other thing that
should look similar

00:43:36.650 --> 00:43:39.470
is that as the reaction
runs for long enough it'll

00:43:39.470 --> 00:43:43.820
reach equilibrium, and you'll
have the lines level out.

00:43:43.820 --> 00:43:45.860
You'll reach an
equilibrium state.

00:43:45.860 --> 00:43:49.950
Now what happens if you
stress that equilibrium state?

00:43:49.950 --> 00:43:54.340
So say you add hydrogen. And
so this line adds the hydrogen,

00:43:54.340 --> 00:43:56.030
then it goes down.

00:43:56.030 --> 00:43:59.840
Then you're also going to use
up some nitrogen as you're

00:43:59.840 --> 00:44:01.790
using up the
hydrogen. You're going

00:44:01.790 --> 00:44:05.300
to shift it to
make more product.

00:44:05.300 --> 00:44:08.570
Now, say, you make product.

00:44:08.570 --> 00:44:11.600
You add product-- sorry,
you're adding product.

00:44:11.600 --> 00:44:16.880
It's going to shift to minimize
the stress, use up the product,

00:44:16.880 --> 00:44:21.020
have the product dissociate,
and make more hydrogen and more

00:44:21.020 --> 00:44:22.800
nitrogen.

00:44:22.800 --> 00:44:25.230
So here's the plot.

00:44:25.230 --> 00:44:28.500
Now, let's just think about
what's happening at each step.

00:44:28.500 --> 00:44:31.400
So if we're adding
more reactant,

00:44:31.400 --> 00:44:32.360
you have more reactant.

00:44:32.360 --> 00:44:34.580
You have too much reactant.

00:44:34.580 --> 00:44:39.800
Shift to minimize the
stress, and you will shift

00:44:39.800 --> 00:44:41.390
the reaction toward product.

00:44:41.390 --> 00:44:43.760
Get rid of the reactant,
use up the reactant.

00:44:43.760 --> 00:44:46.780
Let's get back to the
equilibrium condition,

00:44:46.780 --> 00:44:49.220
minimize the stress.

00:44:49.220 --> 00:44:54.126
Now, we can think about this
in terms of Q and K again.

00:44:57.030 --> 00:45:01.580
So when you have
reactants added,

00:45:01.580 --> 00:45:05.850
then Q is going to fall
below K momentarily.

00:45:05.850 --> 00:45:09.620
And so that means-- if you think
about our equation over here,

00:45:09.620 --> 00:45:13.130
recall this equation,
this important equation.

00:45:13.130 --> 00:45:18.170
So with Q less than K, you
get a negative delta G,

00:45:18.170 --> 00:45:21.200
and that's going to be
spontaneous toward the right,

00:45:21.200 --> 00:45:22.440
toward products.

00:45:22.440 --> 00:45:26.240
So again, you respond
by making more products.

00:45:26.240 --> 00:45:29.720
You shift to the right.

00:45:29.720 --> 00:45:31.390
And you saw that over here.

00:45:31.390 --> 00:45:33.890
It's shifting toward products.

00:45:33.890 --> 00:45:37.040
You're using up the hydrogen.
You're using up the nitrogen.

00:45:37.040 --> 00:45:41.390
You're trying to return to
an equilibrium condition.

00:45:41.390 --> 00:45:47.360
Now what happens if
we add more product?

00:45:47.360 --> 00:45:51.230
And so when you're adding more
product, Q is greater than K

00:45:51.230 --> 00:45:51.890
momentarily.

00:45:51.890 --> 00:45:55.910
You have too many products
now compared to equilibrium.

00:45:55.910 --> 00:46:02.360
And when Q is greater than K,
you get a positive delta G.

00:46:02.360 --> 00:46:04.250
And that means that
it's spontaneous

00:46:04.250 --> 00:46:06.680
in the reverse direction,
or non-spontaneous

00:46:06.680 --> 00:46:08.160
in the forward direction.

00:46:08.160 --> 00:46:09.710
So you shift toward reactants.

00:46:09.710 --> 00:46:11.910
You shift to the left.

00:46:11.910 --> 00:46:13.460
So again, you can
use this equation

00:46:13.460 --> 00:46:17.550
to think about what direction
is now going to be favorable.

00:46:17.550 --> 00:46:19.610
And so here you added product.

00:46:19.610 --> 00:46:21.140
The product gets used up.

00:46:21.140 --> 00:46:23.210
It's shifting toward
reactants, and you're

00:46:23.210 --> 00:46:27.590
making more reactants until
you reach equilibrium again.

00:46:27.590 --> 00:46:32.060
And we have one minute left
for a last clicker question.

00:46:32.060 --> 00:46:33.990
What happens when
you remove products?

00:46:54.631 --> 00:46:55.130
All right.

00:46:55.130 --> 00:46:56.795
So let's just take
10 more seconds.

00:47:08.670 --> 00:47:11.130
All right.

00:47:11.130 --> 00:47:13.540
So we'll just put
it up over here.

00:47:13.540 --> 00:47:15.690
So that means that
delta G is going

00:47:15.690 --> 00:47:19.580
to be negative in that case
because you remove products.

00:47:19.580 --> 00:47:22.710
So Q is less than K,
and so the reaction

00:47:22.710 --> 00:47:25.170
is going to be spontaneous
in the forward direction.

00:47:25.170 --> 00:47:26.910
Delta G will be
negative, and you'll

00:47:26.910 --> 00:47:28.710
move to make more products.

00:47:28.710 --> 00:47:30.870
Again, minimize the stress.

00:47:30.870 --> 00:47:32.080
You took away products.

00:47:32.080 --> 00:47:33.780
You need to make more.

00:47:33.780 --> 00:47:36.620
Minimize the stress.

00:47:36.620 --> 00:47:40.650
Do problem set 5 and
minimize your stress.

